default2.9.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultOn the former there
default is a need for responsibilities 
defaultfor local rail networks to be devolved (as has already happened successfully in Scotland
default, on Merseyrail Electrics and on London Overground). 
defaultBus services (the main form of public transport outside London and the South East) are deregulated outside London which means that PTEs can only provide services where commercial services have not been p
defaultrovided. PTEs (and local government elsewhere outside London) have t
defaultherefore very limited control over
default fares and service levels. There are powers in the Local Transport Act 2008 which strengthen the role of PTEs in a deregulated environment (and which are 
defaultbeing deployed)
default,
default and also powers to introduce the franchising of bus services (the same system that is used to provide bus services in London) whic
defaulth Nexus (Tyne and Wear PTE) has
default triggered. Having limited abilities to plan public transport sets the PTEs ap
defaultart from TfL and counterparts for European cities. 
default2.10.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultHowever, this could be changed if national government worked with the city regions in partnership and in a consistent way over a concerted period to devolve and enhance the powers that PTEs have o
defaultver publ
defaultic transport and 
defaultto crack the obstacles that stand in the way of providing integrated public transport for the city regions. 
