default2.12.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultAs set out above
default,
default one of the obstacles to devolution of transport decision maki
defaultng in England outside London is its complex economic and social geography. The best way of dealing with cross boundary schemes
default,
default or schemes with major
default cross-boundary
default impact
defaults,
default is therefore to some extent determined by local circumstances
default,
default however there are some factors to consider. 
default
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultdifferent types of transport decisions may be best devolved to different tiers of sub-national governance. So for example decisions on local roads may be best dealt with at a relatively low level tier of local 
defaultgovernment. Other decisions - for example in a city region - on local public transport netw
defaultorks are best dealt with at the city region
default level. However
default,
default there are other issues that may best be dealt with at a higher tier - such as is proposed on a devolved N
defaultorthern Rail service. The principle is to devolve where possible to the most appropriate level of governance for the nature of the decision to be taken. 
default
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultwhatever arrangements are made for decision-making ther
defaulte
default will always 
defaultbe boundary issues 
defaultas boundaries 
defaulthave to be drawn somewhere and there will still be journeys made across those boundaries. Although these boundary issues cannot be eliminated
default,
default they can be minimised if sensible and rational decisions 
defaultare taken 
defaultabout devolving the right decisions to the rig
defaultht level of governance
default. 
default
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultif relatively low levels of local transport funding are devolved to small units of local government then there is a danger that no single area will have sufficient funding to build more expensive and significant schemes (where 
defaultthey
default are justified). This 
defaultcomes back to devolving to the appropriate tier of governance. Again the PTEs are an example of t
defaulthis as they are able to pool and prioritise expenditure across a meaningful area.
